    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-04-26T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-04-26T03:00:00-05:00" n="818"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d818">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114 Supplies/4–2645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-04-26T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 26, 1945—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 26—6:23 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1352. ReEmbs 872, March 23, 4 p.m. Embassy has received note from Foreign Office
                    dated April 24 stating that Japanese Embassy in Moscow informed Foreign Office
                    on April 7 that Japanese Government had decided to send to Nakhodka the <hi
                        rend="italic">Awa Maru</hi>, a vessel of 11,200 tons displacement to
                    transport cargo to Allied prisoners of <pb facs="1073" n="1061" xml:id="pg_1061"
                    /> war in Japan and that the vessel would be ready to proceed to Nakhodka the
                    middle of April.</p>
                <p>Note continues that on April 18 Foreign Office received second note from Japanese
                    Embassy stating that Japanese Government had been obliged to cancel the planned
                    dispatch of the <hi rend="italic">Awa Maru</hi> since the vessel has been lost
                    on a return voyage from the south where “it had delivered the first part of a
                    cargo” and that the Japanese Embassy had alleged in its note that it had learned
                    from an official American statement that the <hi rend="italic">Awa Maru</hi> had
                    been sunk by a United Nations submarine in spite of a guarantee of safe conduct
                    given by the United Nations.<note n="45" xml:id="d818fn45">For documentation
                        concerning the sinking of the <hi rend="italic">Awa Maru</hi>, see <ref
                            target="frus1945v06">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>
                        </ref>, section under Japan entitled “Sinking by a United States submarine
                        of the Japanese ship <hi rend="italic">Awa Maru</hi>…”</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Soviet note is not clear as to exactly what is meant by the “first part of a
                    cargo”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
